  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Aware, BeanFactoryAware, BeanNameAware, DisposableBean, InitializingBean, ApplicationContextAware, ChannelInterceptorAware, ExecutorChannelInterceptorAware, QueueChannelOperations, ExpressionCapable, NamedComponent, ConfigurableMetricsAware<AbstractMessageChannelMetrics>, IntegrationManagement, IntegrationStatsManagement, MessageChannelMetrics, PollableChannelManagement, QueueChannelManagement, TrackableComponent, MessageChannel, PollableChannel

    public class PriorityChannel
extends QueueChannel
    A message channel that prioritizes messages based on a Comparator. The default comparator is based upon the message header's 'priority'.
    Author:
    Mark Fisher, Oleg Zhurakousky, Gary Russell, Artem Bilan

      • PriorityChannel

      • PriorityChannel

        Parameters:

      • PriorityChannel

        public PriorityChannel(Comparator<Message<?>> comparator)
        Create a channel with an unbounded queue. Message priority will be determined by the provided Comparator. If the comparator is null, the priority will be based upon the value of IntegrationMessageHeaderAccessor.getPriority().
        Parameters:
        comparator - The comparator.

      • PriorityChannel

        public PriorityChannel(int capacity,
                       @Nullable
                       Comparator<Message<?>> comparator)
        Create a channel with the specified queue capacity. If the capacity is a non-positive value, the queue will be unbounded. Message priority will be determined by the provided Comparator. If the comparator is null, the priority will be based upon the value of IntegrationMessageHeaderAccessor.getPriority().
        Parameters:
        capacity - The capacity.
        comparator - The comparator.

      • doSend

        protected boolean doSend(Message<?> message,
                         long timeout)
        Description copied from class: AbstractMessageChannel
        Subclasses must implement this method. A non-negative timeout indicates how long to wait if the channel is at capacity (if the value is 0, it must return immediately with or without success). A negative timeout value indicates that the method should block until either the message is accepted or the blocking thread is interrupted.
        Overrides:
        doSend in class QueueChannel
        Parameters:
        message - The message.
        timeout - The timeout.
        Returns:
        true if the send was successful.

      • doReceive

        protected Message<?> doReceive(long timeout)
        Description copied from class: AbstractPollableChannel
        Subclasses must implement this method. A non-negative timeout indicates how long to wait if the channel is empty (if the value is 0, it must return immediately with or without success). A negative timeout value indicates that the method should block until either a message is available or the blocking thread is interrupted.
        Overrides:
        doReceive in class QueueChannel
        Parameters:
